Even though they have
the money, there's just

00:54:27.295 --> 00:54:28.620
five or six loaves of bread.

00:54:28.620 --> 00:54:31.020
And there there's so many
more people waiting outside.

00:54:31.020 --> 00:54:32.880
Again, Walid Ebeid
here depicting

00:54:32.880 --> 00:54:40.050
a lot of the injustices
that were taking place,

00:54:40.050 --> 00:54:43.220
a lot of the police
brutality against some

00:54:43.220 --> 00:54:47.400
of the Egyptians in the 2007--
again 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010

00:54:47.400 --> 00:54:50.820
led to a lot of anger
in the streets of Egypt.

00:54:50.820 --> 00:54:54.090
I love this work by Mohssin
Haraki, a Moroccan artist

00:54:54.090 --> 00:54:57.450
who talks about the
fossilization of education

00:54:57.450 --> 00:54:58.350
in Morocco.

00:54:58.350 --> 00:55:00.540
So as you see here, he has--

00:55:00.540 --> 00:55:03.510
not only does he have
the history book,

00:55:03.510 --> 00:55:06.510
he has the religious
studies book

00:55:06.510 --> 00:55:09.400
also as part of the series.

00:55:09.400 --> 00:55:11.610
But I love that he
has the Constitution.

00:55:11.610 --> 00:55:13.950
So he says that the Constitution
is not being updated.

00:55:13.950 --> 00:55:14.690
It's fossilized.

00:55:14.690 --> 00:55:15.940
It's become cemented.

00:55:15.940 --> 00:55:20.070
So again, artists are talking
about political issues

00:55:20.070 --> 00:55:21.580
through their art in the region.

00:55:21.580 --> 00:55:26.010
This is a work that we got into
some hot water in Singapore

00:55:26.010 --> 00:55:27.030
when we showed it.

00:55:27.030 --> 00:55:30.791
It's a piece by Sharif Waked,
the Palestinian artist.

00:55:30.791 --> 00:55:33.290
Basically, when you see this,
what's the first word you see?

00:55:33.290 --> 00:55:35.261
What's the first
word you think of?

00:55:35.261 --> 00:55:35.760
Quick.

00:55:35.760 --> 00:55:37.050
AUDIENCE: ISIS.

00:55:37.050 --> 00:55:38.850
SULTAN SOOUD AL
QASSEMI: ISIS, wow.

00:55:38.850 --> 00:55:39.897
OK, another word?

00:55:39.897 --> 00:55:40.730
AUDIENCE: Terrorist.

00:55:40.730 --> 00:55:42.396
SULTAN SOOUD AL
QASSEMI: Terrorist, yes.

00:55:42.396 --> 00:55:44.710
OK, so I'm not sure ISIS
has done this before,

00:55:44.710 --> 00:55:46.980
but you're right.

00:55:46.980 --> 00:55:47.897
AUDIENCE: Top of mind.

00:55:47.897 --> 00:55:49.646
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI:
Top of your mind.

00:55:49.646 --> 00:55:52.170
So basically, I want to
explain this work for you,

00:55:52.170 --> 00:55:55.810
because it's very important.

00:55:55.810 --> 00:56:00.690
Sharif Waked talks about
how you judge people

00:56:00.690 --> 00:56:02.135
from the first hand--

00:56:02.135 --> 00:56:03.010
from the first sight.

00:56:03.010 --> 00:56:05.190
Here, he talks about
this individual

00:56:05.190 --> 00:56:09.125
that you immediately assume
is someone who wants to die.

00:56:09.125 --> 00:56:10.750
However, when you
play the video, which

00:56:10.750 --> 00:56:13.230
I will not be playing
for you to save time,

00:56:13.230 --> 00:56:16.200
he is reading a book.

00:56:16.200 --> 00:56:17.860
What's the book
that he's reading?

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:20.670
He's reading a book,
"1,001 Arabian Nights."

00:56:20.670 --> 00:56:23.100
And I'm sure you know the story
of "1,001 Arabian Nights."

00:56:23.100 --> 00:56:26.112
Someone tell me the story quick.

00:56:26.112 --> 00:56:27.919
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:27.919 --> 00:56:29.460
SULTAN SOOUD AL
QASSEMI: Scheherazade

00:56:29.460 --> 00:56:31.240
tells what to Shahryar?

00:56:31.240 --> 00:56:32.460
What does she want from him?

00:56:32.460 --> 00:56:33.690
AUDIENCE: To keep her alive.

00:56:33.690 --> 00:56:34.660
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI:
To keep her alive.

00:56:34.660 --> 00:56:35.579
Does she want to die?

00:56:35.579 --> 00:56:36.120
AUDIENCE: No.

00:56:36.120 --> 00:56:37.260
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI:
She doesn't want to die.

00:56:37.260 --> 00:56:39.130
She wants to live another day.

00:56:39.130 --> 00:56:41.362
Likewise, this individual
doesn't want to die.

00:56:41.362 --> 00:56:42.570
He wants to live another day.

00:56:42.570 --> 00:56:44.790
So that's the idea of the work.

00:56:44.790 --> 00:56:47.340
A lot of artists, like
Ali Cherri of Lebanon,

00:56:47.340 --> 00:56:51.480
depicted contemporary events
with this 2011 uprising.

00:56:51.480 --> 00:56:54.210
Or Sulafa Hijazi, which I
love this work very much, very

00:56:54.210 --> 00:56:55.470
controversial.

00:56:55.470 --> 00:56:59.110
Does anybody here want to
imagine what it's about?

00:56:59.110 --> 00:57:03.330
So you all know the story of
Rapunzel, the German fable.

00:57:03.330 --> 00:57:06.190
So the idea here is
that some of the clerics

00:57:06.190 --> 00:57:08.730
are giving a helping hand
for some of the militants

00:57:08.730 --> 00:57:09.810
to rise up.

00:57:09.810 --> 00:57:13.410
So Sulafa Hijazi is a
Syrian based in Berlin,

00:57:13.410 --> 00:57:14.640
a very controversial piece.

00:57:14.640 --> 00:57:16.514
I have another controversial
piece coming up.

00:57:16.514 --> 00:57:18.750
So if you feel offended,
you should look away now.

00:57:18.750 --> 00:57:22.800
So this is a work, again,
by Sulafa Hijazi from 2011.

00:57:22.800 --> 00:57:26.190
She's talking, basically,
about these soldiers who

00:57:26.190 --> 00:57:29.310
feel that they have some
kind of raw emotion,

00:57:29.310 --> 00:57:32.250
that they get sexually
aroused in a way when

00:57:32.250 --> 00:57:34.980
it comes to seeing
protesters in the street.

00:57:34.980 --> 00:57:36.840
They see them
protesting, and they

00:57:36.840 --> 00:57:38.476
get that they want
to shoot their load.

00:57:38.476 --> 00:57:39.600
They want to go after them.

00:57:39.600 --> 00:57:40.474
You know what I mean?

00:57:40.474 --> 00:57:44.880
They're almost like an
animalistic feeling.

00:57:44.880 --> 00:57:46.280
This work, I really like.

00:57:46.280 --> 00:57:48.930
Abdulnasser Gharem was
a lieutenant colonel,

00:57:48.930 --> 00:57:51.180
I think, in the Saudi Air Force.

00:57:51.180 --> 00:57:54.870
And in 2009, he created
this work called,

00:57:54.870 --> 00:57:57.287
"No More Tears," where he
took the stickers of-- you

00:57:57.287 --> 00:57:58.245
know Johnson &amp; Johnson?

00:57:58.245 --> 00:57:58.745
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:58.745 --> 00:57:59.459
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:57:59.459 --> 00:58:01.500
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI:
I'm sure your moms all--

00:58:01.500 --> 00:58:03.640
you showered as kids
in Johnson &amp; Johnson.

00:58:03.640 --> 00:58:07.500
And so he removed the
Johnson &amp; Johnson stickers,

00:58:07.500 --> 00:58:10.440
and he placed them on a
map of the Arab world.

00:58:13.140 --> 00:58:16.980
So in 2009, you can imagine,
what were the trouble spots?

00:58:16.980 --> 00:58:18.840
Someone tell me, what
were the trouble spots

00:58:18.840 --> 00:58:19.590
of the Arab world?

00:58:19.590 --> 00:58:20.053
AUDIENCE: Iraq.

00:58:20.053 --> 00:58:20.516
AUDIENCE: Syria.

00:58:20.516 --> 00:58:20.980
AUDIENCE: Palestine.

00:58:20.980 --> 00:58:22.230
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI: Iraq.

00:58:22.230 --> 00:58:24.720
Iraq, Palestine, Somalia.

00:58:24.720 --> 00:58:25.730
No, in 2009.

00:58:25.730 --> 00:58:27.030
AUDIENCE: South Sudan.

00:58:27.030 --> 00:58:29.100
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI:
South Sudan, 2009.

00:58:29.100 --> 00:58:30.930
The interesting thing
also-- before we

00:58:30.930 --> 00:58:32.850
move to the next work,
the interesting thing

00:58:32.850 --> 00:58:38.850
about this work is, what
do the no more tears drops

00:58:38.850 --> 00:58:40.580
look like as well.

00:58:40.580 --> 00:58:41.247
AUDIENCE: Blood.

00:58:41.247 --> 00:58:42.538
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI: Blood?

00:58:42.538 --> 00:58:43.038
Good.

00:58:43.038 --> 00:58:43.537
And?

00:58:43.537 --> 00:58:44.610
AUDIENCE: Bombs, I guess.

00:58:44.610 --> 00:58:46.180
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI:
No, something else.

00:58:46.180 --> 00:58:47.170
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:47.170 --> 00:58:47.900
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI: No.

00:58:47.900 --> 00:58:49.220
What do we export in the Gulf?

00:58:49.220 --> 00:58:50.030
AUDIENCE: Oil.

00:58:50.030 --> 00:58:50.450
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI: Oil.

00:58:50.450 --> 00:58:53.240
They look like oil, drops of
oil, when you look at them.

00:58:53.240 --> 00:58:57.260
Anyway, so what he did
was that he revisits--

00:58:57.260 --> 00:59:01.730
in 2014, he revisits
the theme of this work.

00:59:01.730 --> 00:59:03.920
And he creates an
updated version.

00:59:03.920 --> 00:59:05.795
Can you imagine what happened?

00:59:05.795 --> 00:59:06.950
Do you want to see?

00:59:06.950 --> 00:59:07.792
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:59:07.792 --> 00:59:09.750
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI:
This is what happened.

00:59:09.750 --> 00:59:11.020
It's all over the region.

00:59:11.020 --> 00:59:14.560
There's really the agony and
sadness all over the region--

00:59:14.560 --> 00:59:17.460
in Libya, in Syria,
in Tunis, in Yemen.

00:59:17.460 --> 00:59:19.064
AUDIENCE: In spite
of the three drops

00:59:19.064 --> 00:59:21.549
that weren't on the map
in the previous one,

00:59:21.549 --> 00:59:24.040
was he hinting that they
were going somewhere?

00:59:24.040 --> 00:59:26.456
SULTAN SOOUD AL QASSEMI: Maybe
he's predicting the future.

00:59:26.456 --> 00:59:27.425
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:59:27.425 --> 00:59:29.050
SULTAN SOOUD AL
QASSEMI: More to come--

00:59:29.050 --> 00:59:31.580
another bigger-- they're
bigger and bigger.

00:59:31.580 --> 00:59:34.382
Yeah, it's a disaster.

00:59:34.382 --> 00:59:35.340
So this is interesting.

00:59:35.340 --> 00:59:37.560
We have one work
left to show you.

00:59:37.560 --> 00:59:39.810
So a lot of people
in the Gulf, they're

00:59:39.810 --> 00:59:42.060
very careful when they're
critical of the governments.

00:59:42.060 --> 00:59:43.717
And so you don't
see a lot of artwork

00:59:43.717 --> 00:59:45.300
that are critical
of governments here.

00:59:45.300 --> 00:59:49.680
But this is an interesting
piece by a GCC artist

00:59:49.680 --> 00:59:52.200
called the GCC,
the micro-council.

00:59:52.200 --> 00:59:54.570
The collective is called
the GCC Collective.

00:59:54.570 --> 00:59:56.640
And this work from 2014 is it--

00:59:56.640 --> 01:00:00.450
2013, they create--
they recreate

01:00:00.450 --> 01:00:06.276
the GCC, the table where
they meet, all the leaders.

01:00:06.276 --> 01:00:07.650
And you look at
the work, and you

01:00:07.650 --> 01:00:10.580
think, oh, it's very beautiful.

01:00:10.580 --> 01:00:11.910
All the flags are there.

01:00:11.910 --> 01:00:15.150
The rubbish bins are made
of gold or whatever that is.

01:00:15.150 --> 01:00:16.170
They're all meeting.

01:00:16.170 --> 01:00:19.350
However, most Kuwaitis
have much more leeway

01:00:19.350 --> 01:00:22.677
and freedom when it comes
to political discussion.

01:00:22.677 --> 01:00:24.135
They wanted to put
them in context.

01:00:28.570 --> 01:00:30.300
So you can imagine.

01:00:30.300 --> 01:00:33.950
So what the message basically
is that you will be scrutinized.

01:00:33.950 --> 01:00:36.600
So when you visit this work
and you walk next to it,

01:00:36.600 --> 01:00:40.350
you look down and you
scrutinize the meeting--

01:00:40.350 --> 01:00:42.480
the meeting and the
leaders themselves.

01:00:42.480 --> 01:00:44.380
So this is the whole
idea of the work.

01:00:44.380 --> 01:00:48.870
So this is how Kuwaitis sort
of interact with events here

01:00:48.870 --> 01:00:50.440
in the region.

01:00:50.440 --> 01:00:52.280
Very last work that
I will show you,

01:00:52.280 --> 01:00:57.400
unfortunately, is the work I
feel that reflects the region.

01:00:57.400 --> 01:01:00.050
I'm always sad to
end with this piece.

01:01:00.050 --> 01:01:02.240
It's a piece by
Mona Hatoum, who was

01:01:02.240 --> 01:01:04.650
a Beirut-born, Palestinian
artist now based

01:01:04.650 --> 01:01:07.530
in the UK-- is very, very
important, had solo exhibitions

01:01:07.530 --> 01:01:09.350
all over the world.

01:01:09.350 --> 01:01:11.580
Mona Hatoum's
"Infinity" basically

01:01:11.580 --> 01:01:13.920
encompasses the region.

01:01:13.920 --> 01:01:18.960
What you see is soldiers
standing in eternal fights,

01:01:18.960 --> 01:01:20.760
shooting each other forever.

01:01:20.760 --> 01:01:24.120
They are depicted as
toys, because they

01:01:24.120 --> 01:01:26.070
are being controlled by others.

01:01:26.070 --> 01:01:27.780
They are replaceable.

01:01:27.780 --> 01:01:29.640
Have you ever seen
the green soldiers?

01:01:29.640 --> 01:01:33.017
When you lose one of them,
you just buy another batch.

01:01:33.017 --> 01:01:35.100
So the idea is that they
really keep replenishing.

01:01:35.100 --> 01:01:36.300
They're never-ending.

01:01:36.300 --> 01:01:39.970
And they're also placed
on a coffee table.

01:01:39.970 --> 01:01:42.050
And the idea of placing
them on a coffee table

01:01:42.050 --> 01:01:45.900
is to show you how
wars are domesticated.

01:01:45.900 --> 01:01:48.701
Wars have effects
on the household.

01:01:48.701 --> 01:01:50.200
And I feel like
this really reflects

01:01:50.200 --> 01:01:55.290
the region where you have
eternal, perpetual wars, wars

01:01:55.290 --> 01:01:58.280
that affect the region,
where people are almost

01:01:58.280 --> 01:02:03.240
standing constantly with a gun
to the back of someone else,

01:02:03.240 --> 01:02:06.360
and you never know
what's coming for you,

01:02:06.360 --> 01:02:12.030
and also the idea that there
is always an endless supply

01:02:12.030 --> 01:02:13.410
of available people to fight.

01:02:13.410 --> 01:02:15.130
But this is the end
of the presentation.

01:02:15.130 --> 01:02:15.963
Thank you very much.

01:02:15.963 --> 01:02:18.440
[APPLAUSE]

